The women who "turn around" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the people.
"Men rarely suffer such a thing."
"It also does not isolate healthy young women, because they help in the work and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of West Africa Burkina Faso, occupies a special residence of over a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
It issued an information leaflet that should help to avoid witch hunting.
However, this has a stick.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," warns Die Standard on the disadvantages of written awareness.
Witchcraft accusations are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, a neighbouring country in Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemma died last week, when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared in the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to a wretched accumulation of circumstances.
