The Bakala tenant: is heated with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The old and recio man crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of the "coal magnet" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-storey rental contracts: his, his daughter's and his son's, which is serving sentence.
All three have just caught the liberalisation of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, there is no hot water and heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," he says with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "uncorrect and indecent", recommends to tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, when he will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, in this case, man only makes one suitor.
"Each one says something," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large laboratory for testing liberalization.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the floors that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rental.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of Ostrava's four and on Tuesday at nine o'clock, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a number pickup machine.
"To rent 2011", you can read on a light button on your touch screen.
When you press it, you get out of the machine a little paper with a number.
It hardly gives time or read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Shortly thereafter, an elderly marriage comes to ask, but the crowd of the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as in the past: settlement requests, insurance issues and similar issues.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the lodges of the tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters an increase in rent between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window is opened at the customer service centre for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting," they answer, after they have doubted briefly, the workers who are in it when the customer presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and the old floors for Bakala miners are the most delicate themes in the area.
Before the elections, the Vice-President of Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaoralek, from ČSSD, had already treated them high and clear, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers in the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change my damn bathroom plate," the man mentioned in the introduction was drowned.
According to the workers, for the moment they are more than nothing retired to check whether they receive a discount on rent if they sign in time, as the special RPG offer promises.
They will also receive half of the discount on the rent of February the remaining tenants signing the new contract by 15 December.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the flood of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rental in 2011 about forty-fifty people," said the employee of the window.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its tables to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
