Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides inside a small nursery with everything he owns at such facilities: walls of colors, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of the employees of Arch.Design can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose study came from numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, day care is one of the benefits that Arch.Design your workers in the framework of your social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The miniguard was an idea of Arch.Designu's employees themselves and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guardia is financed through the European Social Fund under the operational programme for human resources and employment, as well as the Czech State budget.
Thanks to the funding provided (an allocation of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to maintain the mini-guard with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted for one year and in the submission of the application for funding contributed the Economy Rating company.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; moreover, a nurse and teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-guardy", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts more come during the day.
The functioning of the day-care centre is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the day-care centre, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guardian programme are comparable to the usual pre-school education programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and table games, but also has a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to their children at any time and avoid the stress of collecting late school children when they are away from their place of work.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the sign companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The bone house continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Batlló House, in Barcelona, by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the bone house".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all of this is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
By paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought order is observed.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us also within it.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the rails, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signposts.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in Eixample district in the number 43 of the lively commercial street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the refurbishment of a house in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on overthrowing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, consisting of several apartments, did not design it Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their project plans, ornaments emerged for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and the Güell Park in Gaudí, where other pieces of it are found.
Because of its organic form, the premises shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the bone house".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of bosteches".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange its forty-five degree inclination.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction rules of the moment at all and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the outset, although obviously in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, upon its completion, the town council was so impacted with the result it requested to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public pavement.
The arrangements were never made, rather, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the city's application, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery of the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented at a jewelry store.
The house, on six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and a larger group can communicate in this manner without problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with the light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which instead absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005.
On the first floor of the house you will find the most spacious and refilled apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and extended visits to the common area and to the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to enjoy the true atmosphere of the bed with your lizard towers, you should quickly become friends with some resident of the neighboring houses and visit you at home.
How the mattress and the somier are chosen: women and men are looking for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really confers its quality on a good bed is the surface to lie down, i.e. the mattress and the somier.
First of all, they must be complemented by perfection in order to adapt to specific users.
Many elements, including weight, height, health status and owner's sex, come into play during the election.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and the somier are placed.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cottage that usually does not have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat" more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
It is therefore necessary to turn them around more frequently.
If the central channels are not properly aired and above, they are on a firm basis, they keep inside the moisture. Even the mold below may appear.
When choosing a bed, customs also influence.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have problems feeling good on a lower and tougher surface.
"Almost all hockey players returning from the NHL complained that they didn't sleep here as well."
"For their bruised shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"This type of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have problems with the nervous system, so they get bad information about the joints and the skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in the covered furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, take time preferring viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech Tropic brand."
You don't have to be a NHL player anymore in order to appreciate viscoelastics.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
Optimizes your rigidity and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not turn like after a hard match.
Just sleep better.
Viscoelastics also works as a protection against the wrinkles.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of its feet, i.e. between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
For individual rooms, for example singles, it is recommended at least between 120 and 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when you fall face up, you should have your hands comfortably shrinked towards the elbows," advises engineer Helena Prokopová, expert from Cechu čalouníkänk to dekorater, who has been busy for many years with the problems of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture, which teaches in specialized schools.
In the double rooms, everyone needs their own somier and mattress, so during the purchase you need to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the somies at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with inner springs a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three cm are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and smoothness.
"By touching it with your hand or staying on the mattress, no doubt the docks should not be noticed," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a particular type of somier.
The fully covered bedrooms, on which the mattress and base are like siames, make no sense in the bedroom.
The mattresses breathe badly and you can't wash your back, which is often done today.
And since every night we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) slum.
For this reason, experts reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a life assurance.
However, everything has one but.
Therefore, sellers give advice: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care of the cleaning and washing of the floor, but better add a mattress protector that can be removed and washed easily.
Although mattress covers are currently manufactured with zip closure throughout its perimeter, so by opening them they are left in two parts (something very important for washing and washing machine size!), their handling in the larger models (and for one person) when lifting the mattress may seem like a fight between a fly weight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a somier, do you have a firm table?
Never!
As much for the beds thought to spend one night the visits.
However, you must make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes on the table and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For somies of non-jointable sheets containing between 14 and 18 sheets, mattresses of latex or sandwich mattresses (e.g. a combination of latex and coconut fiber) may be used, although it is always better to use a somier with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the plates of the lumbar area are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated.
Articular sheet somies should not be used with a spring mattress, since they do not react to reclination.
In addition to the adjustment of the rigidity of the blades, the protection of shoulders can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the blades that allows to press or even tilt the blades in such a way that they "round" perfectly to the shoulders during the sleep.
For men with very wide shoulders, it is something very important.
They even remember the mattress manufacturers who, in the "male", began to use a softer area right around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around their hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are somies with cross structure or tables with so-called multitorsion damping.
Pressure is distributed between different points and tension is lowered.
It should also be taken into account that, although it uses the appropriate mattress and somier, if it uses a bad pillow (large and "waisted"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should hold the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so they can relax their muscles.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying aside, the pillow should be on the same level (when combined with the somier with shoulder reinforcement or the softest area of the mattress) as the shoulder height.
Modern mattresses have something to do, as it seems, with original mattresses filled with straw.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or at least mixtures.
In fact, the biological mattresses are fashionable.
Oil-based raw materials, with which polyurethane foam is manufactured, are filled with natural oils, such as rice or soybeans.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soybeans.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the centre is manufactured only from materials of natural origin," explains Petr Vašíček of the company Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used during the manufacture of the mattress bottom, one of the first true aloe.
But you can also choose the microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma to the forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "refresh" themselves with vegetal extracts of breeze, so that the mattress bottom absorbs heat and cools the body, women prefer to "heat" the floor.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel more warm.
The current favorites?
The mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with a structure of adapted cells, making them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various cold and viscoelastic foam stiffnesses allows the manufacture of mattresses from various areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns upwards.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have lower VAT, as they are considered to be means of health.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and somies.
Sometimes the offers of manufacturers or sellers can be approved, which sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreez mattresses with a foam with memory attached to the back for 11,990 crowns.
The second is obtained free of charge.
The era of viscoelastics with an open cell structure and a large density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
Initially it emerged as material for NASA, because during the takeoffs the astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the human body, warm, exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is used not only on mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
National manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and similar.
More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for the tracking of vehicles, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
For the moment the device has the approximate size of a pair of glasses, but will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people feared the case of missing Anička and began to inform themselves about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to tell us that it is not a matter of spying, but of another means of reducing the possibility of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognise that in certain cases such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet met such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in the event of an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if the child does not want to take him, he will just throw him away.
"Even younger children show great creativity when intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"In the past, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," Bočková says.
In his opinion, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check whether the child wears some type of electronic device that can reveal his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is expanding, you will also look for them, since your sale will no doubt be made with a lot of publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised pedophile attack.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is destroyed immediately, its presence may be helpful.
"You can configure the device to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If you suffer damage, at least you will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices incorporate a tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," Čech says.
In your opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smart mobile phones with navigation, in which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that for the moment these are devices with a size similar to a pair of glasses or smaller mobile phones.
So they can get lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, for that reason tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital clock.
