Senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday that prosecutors from the Department of Justice have excused Senator John Ensign from the criminal charges arising from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to ensure work through lobby for the woman's husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat faced by Ensign, the Republican of Nevada, who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate by 2012, until the scandal over his business had national headlines last year and would damage his career.
Ensign's office said he felt "certainly happy" with the decision, which came after an entire year's investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign's lawyers said that the Department of Justice had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer an objective of his investigation and that he has no plans to raise charges against him on this matter."
The Department of Justice did not wish to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there seemed to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign might have fabbled to violate a federal criminal lobby ban.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents that were first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative work through lobby, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, on the affairs of the senator with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr. Hampton and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was excluded under the law of lobbying for his former employer or Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said that the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared in disagreement with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door status," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While the Department of Justice officials refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed cautious in accepting political proceedings after several major setbacks to its public integrity section, including last year's decision to abandon the prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, in the midst of charges for misconduct.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards," said Melanie Sloan, Executive Director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that filed several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's principal lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor of the Department of Justice on Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to raise charges against his client.
Ensign's defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in trying to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave the prosecutors.
"I don't feel comfortable entering into details about my discussions with the Department of Justice, I can only say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to change an investigation into a complaint separated by the ethics group, which claims that a payment of $96,000 from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated the federal electoral law.
