When news of the affair first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and gave up his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for many months, Ensign told journalists two weeks ago that he planned to apply for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign's spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of criminal investigation, he said that the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and complete its investigation.
" Senator Ensign wishes to continue his difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada," he said.
