They argued that the media kept throwing firewood into the fire of emotion over the case.
"The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the court," the lawyers wrote, "it was something that was never seen here in New Haven and perhaps all over the state."
Your attention to Tweeter's coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that the complaint about the fact that immediate news was more important than the reports given more slowly, was a ludicrous vision that would make the court's policy on coverage control weak in future processes.
But some lawyers said that appeals courts were often attracted by arguments about the adaptation required in the courts due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pressing for that claim.
