Can civicism build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, a bit of civicism has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a premonition of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not produce any progress on the major issues to be dealt with during the outgoing session.
But from what they all say, it was at least a polite discussion of the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The President's deficit committee's public meeting on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates the members.
That is hardly enough to state that a new era of cooperation has come.
Now both parties are in a trial period, testing each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
Reason why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent assessments of the meeting by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and are very deeply rooted as to suggest any rapid change in the climate that existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two parties are in opposite poles.
However, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, an official of Bush's administration now at the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which then go out.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing meeting, the Republicans and Democrats had no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are won at the end of the year, and nobody's in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment subsidies, probably because the Republicans cannot make them believe they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying the unemployment subsidy for the unemployed.
After the Tuesday meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these items during the outgoing session, together with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation in the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanism when the new 112nd. Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable, that a period of disagreement should begin.
"After the things to be done have been done, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to genuine cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, which contributed decisively to its creation.
As the Republican leaders are more aware of the dangers of overstepping their position, they know that they must try to fulfill their promises to cut off state expenses and cancel the new health law.
These support lines are already clearly reflected in initial responses to the recommendations of the deficit commission, including tax reform and increased taxes and retirement age, and cuts in expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been responsible for one of the most difficult work in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the commission of 18 members to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officers elected in the panel, suggesting that there are at least currently few bases or wishes for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House Republicans and Congressmen.
The first will happen next year in the form of supportive shocks, when the Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks he's missing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partyism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties view 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will take much more effort on both sides to find common points on issues that still divide them.
