"The reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our obligation to collect these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Red Jemeres, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the secondary school history textbook of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Red Jemeres.
As in most Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little about the Red Jemers, despite the city's bond with the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said that the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court," he said.
"They have suspicions because they are not sure about the number of people who will prosecute the court."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are starting to produce an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Red Jemers retain a powerful charm.
