Revenge hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it unveils an apparent scandal, a scandal that seems to be just scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file created by a secret service (independent of the nation to which it belongs) is exclusively made up of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculous profile of Khadafi has long given ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be formed by news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of secret services, not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that every work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templaries or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not just because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of secret services (if he couldn't be, I know, libération editor), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. Embassy of Rome to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the previous week.
Why, then, have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, the embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of States can call on the telephone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who sees research films knows perfectly well, we just pretend that we don't know it by hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a poor image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker would be able to consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore affects both the victims and the "venders".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Previously, in Orwell's time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true ever since, being able to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, visited hotel, taken highway, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it now happens, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be endured that can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel once said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like publishing it in a poster in the middle of the street.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential telephone conversations cannot be expected.
Nothing is easier than discovering whether and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and therefore novel, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in due diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
This information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: in the end, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is now progressing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has again created a cable telegraph (telephones).
Video tapes (analogues) had allowed film researchers to study a step-by-step film, moving forward and backwards, discovering all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (digitals) just allow them to move forward or back from chapter to chapter, i.e. to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can travel from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travels it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly framed in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's hats in its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether rapidly unlocked funding promises (called fast start or early) have been respected by developed countries.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute EUR 7.2 billion in three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a great complementary event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparency operation was appreciable and was appreciated for what really was worth: developing countries and civil society wanted all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 €2.2 billion, which puts it on the right path towards fulfilling its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we look at the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, an agreement has not been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the best reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of aid from France to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while seeking to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no rule and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro provided amounts to one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more effective technologies), it is important to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At the most, only the cost of the loan should be calculated for its commitments for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent to an interest rate).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros); consult the EU document to see it in its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union which so frequently uses the loan.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect its commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only provides ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only EUR 36.1 million, it manages to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has taken care of arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States still giving when they can just lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not foolish...
The chapter on early financing is a detail, relatively short-term, in relation to the whole of climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the huge machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn early funding from this first year.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move forward discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister of Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
